Clio-2

Over the past semester, I have taken part in a methods course for data analysis and visualization for historians. I have been introduced to a variety of data types that one might encounter in the process of doing research including geospatial, textual and network data. The visualizations below were created in the R programming language using R Studio (open access).

Netherlands: Parliamentary Elections, 1994-2012

The Rise of Right in Netherlands’ Parliament

In the postcolonial era, a national policy of multiculturalism was adopted by the Dutch government after waves of immigration from former colonies, Southern and Eastern European, as well as Middle-Eastern countries, increasingly diversified country’s population. While the 1990’s brought about an emphasis on assimilation policies, Netherlands’ national politics of multiculturalism became a point of contention and contestation after the murders of Pim Fortuyn (in 2002) and Theo van Gogh (in 2004). Further compounding xenophobic attitudes in the Netherlands, and the EU in general, was the subsequent Euro and Immigration Crises of 2009 and 2011, respectively. Economic and political turmoil further strained the government’s ability to financially and publicly support a national agenda centered on multicultural policies. This general trend in eroding popularity of leftist policies is illustrated in the chart below (Figure 1). The following graphs chart parliamentary elections in the Netherlands for almost two decades (1994-2012) by political alignment and party. For access to the original data see the European Election Database.

From 1994 through 2002, the majority of ballots cast during Dutch Parliamentary elections were overwhelmingly in support of moderate parties (centre, centre-left, centre-right). The 2006 elections mark a definite shift in voter trends away from moderate party alignment in favor of greater support of far-right and far-left factions. This same election year, representation of right-wing parties, by far, the least represented political alignment in the Dutch Parliament, gains a negotiable amount of seats. If we look at the graph below (Figure Two) we can see that the substantial increase in voter support of the far-right is likely due to the emergence of the People’s Freedom Party (PVV) in 2006.

Party Politics

While the increasing polarization in ideological alignment through 2010 is not particularly surprising given economic, political and social climate in the Netherlands (see above), the election results in 2012 are. In terms of political alignment (Figure 1), the increasing popularity and predominance of the PVV and the VVD in recent Dutch Parliamentary elections suggest that voter trends would steadily increase, yet we see a marked hiccup in the 2012 elections. For less ambiguity, let’s turn to the graph below to locate voting shifts along party lines.

Party Key: People’s Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD), Party for Freedom (PPV), Labour Party (PvdA), Socialist Party (SP), Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA), Democrats 66 (D66), Christian Union (CU), GreenLeft (GL), Reformed Political Party (SGP), Party for the Animals (PvdD), 50PLUS (50+)

When examining the graph above, the reader might notice a decrease in support of far right and left parties such as the PVV, the GL and the SP, along with the main moderate (centre) party, the CDA. The centre-right and centre-left parties, the VVD and the PvdA, respectively, command almost 30% of the vote apiece. An explanation of this polarization of the centre requires a little research outside the purview of the data to account for this dramatic shift in voting trends.

The emergency election of 2012 occurred on account of the majority party’s (VVD) to garner support for austerity measures under the Fiscal Compact. Subsequently, the coalition government was dissolved and required a new election to reconstitute the House of Representatives. The party alignments was as such: VVD, CDA, D66 and GL in favor of austerity measures, while the opposition coalition consisted of PVV, CU and SP. The forced election was not a popular outcome among voters, and the PVV unwillingness to cooperate with the majority coalition was located as the primary cause. This was the first election in the PPV’s history that the party lost seats in the House.

Concluding Thoughts

While the visualizations and the data do not address all voting trends shown, such as decreasing support for the GL, the data does bring to light party dynamics within Dutch politics beyond that of party alignment which can be often overlooked if you are coming from an American bipartisan perspective rather than a multi-party system represented in a coalition government. At the same time, coding for party alignment across multiple parties can elucidate overarching social and political trends among voters.

Author’s Note: This dataset would have better facilitated the analysis had it included the most recent data from the 2017 election, but the source of data transcription (European Election Database) has not made this information available. In a future essay or analysis, I might transcribe another dataset inclusive of the most recent election data.

The Rise of the People’s Freedom Party in Parliament

The rise of the Right in Europe’s liberal democracies has been an area of growing interest in sociology, as well as political science and area studies among others. As the radical right reemerges from the dredges of Europe’s history with electoral force, researchers have provided a variety of explanations to elucidate the radical right wing’s reemergence. Two popular explanations will be explored in this data visualization essay: the ethnic competition thesis and popular xenophobia. The ethnic competition thesis focuses specifically on the issue of immigration to explain the emergence of right-winged radical parties. While there are other factors to predict voter support for radical right-winged parties, anti-immigration sentiment is considered one of the strongest predictors (Norris 2005). Furthermore, using individual-level data has shown that in France, Denmark and the Netherlands, voters living in areas with large immigrant populations were significantly more likely to vote for the radical right. The popular xenophobia explanation posits that anti-immigration sentiments are not necessarily associated with economic disparities or competition, but rather growing ethnocentrism. I introduce the popular xenophobia explanation to account for anti-immigration attitudes that largely arise during a demographic transformation of a society that can result in a national “identity crisis” (Koopmans 2005).
In the last data visualization essay, we looked at Netherlands’ Parliamentary elections from 1994-2012. In this essay, we will focus on the elections following the establishment of the People’s Freedom Party (PVV) and the rate of change for immigration by region during that time period.

The graph below shows the percentage of the vote garnered by the PVV by region in the Netherlands.

The data reveals that the PVV’s largest proportion of a regional votes was, by far, won in Limburg. Keeping both the ethnic competition thesis and popular xenophobia explanations for the rise of the right in mind, I turn to immigration data to explore the relationship between the votes garnered in support of the PVV and recent immigration rates by region.

The map below charts the Netherlands and the red dots represent the positive rate of change for each region from 2010 to 2012.

Fig. Two: Rate of Change: Immigration (2010-2012)

Findings

Rather than finding a large increase of immigration in Limburg, the rate of change from 2010-2012 into the region is moderate with respect to fellow regions. Curiously, other regions, such as Groningen, show far less regional voter support for the PVV, while having relatively high rates of immigration.

Analysis

While this finding certainly doesn’t discount the ethnic competition thesis or the popular xenophobia in explaining the rise of the radical right, it does lead me to consider other factors that might result in higher support for right-winged parties, such as the PVV, in some regions besides anti-immigrant sentiments. In the case of Limburg, I might look at the local economy and politics during the 2010 parliamentary election, among other supply and demand-side factors (relative deprivation, anomie/social breakdown, political discontent, etc).

Author’s Note:

The findings may have been more compelling had my data set included the same years as the parliamentary elections data. If I had to do this again, I would have imported and tidied all the regional immigration rates from 1994-2012 for comparability.

Works Referenced

Koopmans, R. (Ed.). (2005). Contested citizenship: Immigration and cultural diversity in Europe (Vol. 25). U of Minnesota Press.

Norris, P. (2005). Radical right: Voters and parties in the electoral market. Cambridge University Press.

Trial of the Major War Criminals Before the International Military Tribunal (IMT)

Nuremberg, 14 November 1945-1 October 1946

Following the unconditional surrender of the Axis powers, on 8 May 1945, the Allies accepted Germany’s surrender, and the International Military Tribunal (IMT) was established to try major Nazi war criminals. The proceedings are published spanning 22 volumes of verbatim and translated transcripts in the four languages used in the trials (English, French, Russian, and German). This visualization essay provides a text and sentiment analysis the first four volumes of the “blue series” (with a focus on Volume I) detailing the official proceedings of the trial of the major war criminals (as opposed to the “green series” detailing the subsequent Nuremberg trials, or the “red series” detailing Nazi conspiracy and aggression). Since I wanted to examine how the subsequent trials on Nazi war crimes were framed, I performed a distanced reading of the first 29 days of proceedings (Volumes I-IV) expecting to find an overwhelming focus on individual perpetrators rather than victims or Nazi organizations. Below are the results from a TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) analysis performed on each volume:

Words of Importance in Blue Series

While the last two volumes concentrate on criminal activities of individual perpetrators, the first volume largely addresses the Leadership Corps of the Nazi Party, an organization declared criminal by Tribunal. To my surprise, this section of the proceeding dealt with the structure and component parts of the Nazi party, condemning the organization(s) through indictment of individual members.

This initial focus on the past regime’s crimes is not necessarily surprising, but upon close-reading of volume I, the organization is decoupled from the larger German population quite strikingly, “All members of the Leadership Corps were active in getting out the vote and insuring the highest possible proportion of “yes” votes. Ortsgruppenleiters and Political Leaders of higher ranks often collaborated with the Gestapo and SD in taking steps to determine those who refused to vote or who voted “no”, and in taking steps against them which went as far as arrest and detention in a concentration camp…The Leadership Corps was also used to prevent German public opinion from reacting against the measures taken against the Jews in the East.” This initial (and superficial) analysis seems partially in agreement with Bernard Geisman’s argument “In the narrative of individual criminal guilt, the German people … take the position of the third party … . The law court was the institutional arena in which the demarcation of individual guilt was staged, ritually reconstructed,and reaffirmed” (Giesen 2004,p. 121). Rather than individual guilt, however, the organization as a whole is indicated in its criminality. This is likely to act as a cleansing process to make way for a democratic society dependent on accountability through the rule of law (Savelsberg 2007, p.193). The nature of the indictments might be further illuminated by performing a sentiment analysis of the first volume.

Sentiment Analysis of Volume I

Figure Two: Word counts that contribute to each sentiment in volume I of the blue series.

The sentiment in volume I of the blue series is overwhelmingly negative and the most popular negatively associated words in the volume use legal language whose default logic is largely individualizing in nature (i.e. “criminal”, “guilty” as applied to the defendant). Upon further inspection of the document, volume I uses the term “attack” to describe amorphous “Nazi Conspirators”, while, more notably, “criminal” is used in conjunction to not only individual and group responsibility for criminal activity, but also organization responsibility.

This finding could be more or less interesting due to the commonly held critique of the Nuremberg Trials to focus almost exclusively on individual perpetrators in the Nazi regime and thus, failing to address issues of collective guilt, possibly perpetuating the “cycles of violence” (Minow 2002).

Final Remarks

This text analysis of the blue series of the Trial of the Major War Criminals would be further strengthen (and possibly more interesting) by performing a pairwise correlation and visualization summarizing the strength of relationship between often individualizing legal indictments, such as “criminal” and “guilty”, and the nature of “Nazi Conspirators” (whether they be individuals, groups or organizations). Another, more in depth, analysis might provide insight to the entire corpus as well.

Works Referenced

Giesen B. 2004. The trauma of perpetrators: the Holocaust as the traumatic reference of German national identity. See Alexander et al. 2004, pp. 112–54

Minow M. 2002. Breaking the Cycles of Hatred: Memory, Law, and Repair, ed. NL Rosenblum. Princeton, NJ: Princeton Univ. Press
